1. Setup Project Structure (Local)

MyAutomationProject/
│
├── tests/                 # All your test scripts
│   ├── test_login.py
│   └── test_checkout.py
│
├── pages/                 # Page Object Models (if using POM)
│   ├── login_page.py
│   └── checkout_page.py
│
├── utils/                 # Utility scripts (like helpers, config reader)
│   └── helpers.py
│
├── reports/               # Test reports (generated after tests)
│
├── requirements.txt       # List of Python packages your project needs
├── pytest.ini             # Pytest configuration file
└── README.md              # Project description

Why this structure?
tests/ is for actual test scripts.
pages/ is for Selenium Page Objects (keeps UI interaction separate from tests).
utils/ keeps helper functions centralized.
requirements.txt makes it easy to share your project and install dependencies with pip install -r requirements.txt.

2. Initialize Git Locally
cd MyAutomationProject
git init                  # Initialize Git in your local folder
git add .                 # Stage all files
git commit -m "Initial commit with project structure"

3. Connect Local Repo to GitHub
1. Create a Repo on GitHub (MyAutomationProject)
2. Link local repo to Github
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/MyAutomationProject.git
git branch -M main        # Rename local branch to main (optional but standard)
git push -u origin main   # Push initial code to GitHub

After you've connected your local repo to GitHub and pushed the initial main branch
Now your local main branch is synced with GithUBs main branch.






